>>64754247
Texturing is actually really easy, at least compared to rest of the process. There's billion youtube guides that hand hold you through it. The tl:dr is assign materials, mark some seams, let blender unwrap it in UV view, maybe fiddle with the UV and get drawing/editing. I don't actually know what exactly you're working on, but if you plan on having your models do plenty of movement, you can get away with topology that is just "good enough". With motion and focus being somewhere else it's not that visible. It's actually a really shit feel to spend hours modeling some autistic detail then go "wow it's fucking hidden 99% of the time" so don't fall into that trap. Sega saturn isn't my thing but I get that you're going for low poly. You still absolutely need way more vertices at knees if they're meant to bend, or they'll pop like those tall juice boxes the moment you deform the legs. Good luck with your project, Anon. Most people give up on 3d modeling 15 minutes on or so.
